Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` without opening a real port. Then wire that client into the MCP C# SDK's transport.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol   # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test (xUnit)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>, IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;
    private IMcpClient? _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    private async Task<IMcpClient> CreateClientAsync()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives an HttpClient bound to
        // the in-memory test server — no real port needed.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // adjust the path to match your server's MCP endpoint
            },
            httpClient   // ← inject the test HttpClient
        );

        _client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);
        return _client;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var client = await CreateClientAsync();

        var tools = await client.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsExpectedResult()
    {
        var client = await CreateClientAsync();

        var result = await client.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains(result.Content, c => c.Text!.Contains("expected"));
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        if (_client is not null)
            await _client.DisposeAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your real `Program.cs` pipeline (middleware, DI, routing) in-process.
- Pass the factory's `HttpClient` directly to `SseClientTransport` (or `StreamableHttpClientTransport` if you use Streamable HTTP) so all traffic stays in-memory.
- Override services for testing with `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))`.
- Make sure `Program` is accessible to your test project (add `InternalsVisibleTo` or a `public partial class Program { }` marker).
